      <title>Highland ghost stories</title>
      <author> deekaede </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1808593/highland-ghost-stories/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1808593-highland-ghost-stories/chapter/1817910/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">e4ef25477898885161f648acd1db7b48dd2da004</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 05 Sep 2025 21:17:31 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Ailis returns to their ancestral home. However, what awaits them is something beyond their wildest dreams.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1808593-highland-ghost-stories/chapter/1817910/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;A seasoned beginning.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;     In our modern age, we have a proclivity towards believing that everything has a logical explanation. That all of the world can simply be explained, quantified, reified, and understood using simple means. We never give a thought about the old folktales and whether they were actually true in any way shape or form. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;     We also, most certainly, never think that what we took for granted could be upended in such a world-shattering way. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;     Ailis Williamson Gunn was one such person. The only thing that stood out about him was his dual citizenship in the United States and the United Kingdom. He had this due to his mother having still retained her United Kingdom citizenship. When he finally began college at the age of 20, he had cast a wide net, and was rather surprised when he was accepted at the University of Edinburgh, Scotland.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;              However, Ailis had no real attachment to the United States or the city he lived in prior to being accepted. After all, he was an orphan. He had no family, no meaningful possessions, nor did he have any real friends who kept him attached to the town he grew up in. So, it was easy to accept such a far-flung college from where he lived. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              Which is how Ailis found himself in London Heathrow processing through customs. As he finally made it to the customs counter, the worker gave him a simple glance before she spoke. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              “Good afternoon young lady, do you have anything to declare?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              Ailis’ cheeks flushed slightly at the comment. At 5 foot 5 inches and having a smaller frame, Ailis’ features could best be described as “delicate” rather than masculine by any measure. His lips curled into a slight pout before he responded. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              “Um… no I don’t” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;     Indeed, Ailis was a little bit timid, and tended to lack the courage to correct people. Though he often reasoned there simply wasn’t any reason to do so since he would likely never see them again. Instead, he let it go with that line, and waited for the lady to finish her work. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          He nervously glanced at the clock on the nearby wall, seeing it was still an hour before his connecting train to Edinburgh. So, he felt comfortable in knowing that he still had some time to spare. The process for getting the train tickets as well as the flight ticket were thankfully easy, though it did take a fair bit of the limited savings he had in order to buy it all.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          Carefully, Ailis navigated the airport after clearing customs. He felt overwhelmed by the volume of people as well as the noise. Though, within a few minutes, Ailis began to adjust to the general pace and nature of the airport, learning how to tune out superfluous information in their mind. Ailis’ eyes wandered across the boutiques and shops in the airport, then allowed himself to come to a brief stop.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          While standing in front of a clothing store, Ailis became dimly aware of his somewhat reserved demeanor. He stood with one arm crossed over his chest, gripping his other arm with a somewhat uneasy expression on his face. His shy eyes were slightly downcast so as to avoid making eye contact with other people. All in all, he realized, it was a slightly pathetic sight to see. But then, he wasn’t entirely certain about how to carry himself. He wasn’t fully American, nor was he fully British. He seemed to occupy a middle ground, trying to find some direction by which to proceed in life. With a slight sigh of frustration, he decided to actually look up. Which was when he noticed the store he stopped outside of.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          It looked to be a rather upscale clothing store. Based upon the appearance, it was a women’s clothing store at that. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;           Inside he could see various outfits on display. The current seasons fashion was proudly visible to all, practically begging people to come inside and buy. However, the price tag was enough to keep Ailis from acting on this impulse. But he had to admit, the dress on a mannequin did actually look rather cute. Especially as it had been accessorized quite smartly. All in all, it was a very cute outfit and quite the contrast to his rather plain, yet somewhat gender-neutral choice of slacks which fit slightly wrong around his upper legs and a loose yet plain T-shirt which seemed as if it hung a bit tightly around his chest area.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;              Compared to the outfit the mannequin wore, Ailis realized, his own choice of attire was rather plain and boring. However, he reasoned it was entirely to do with the fact that he grew up in an orphanage and had limited means to buy clothing which really suited his body type. Let alone his tastes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;              Ailis didn’t realize that he was subconsciously thinking about how it would look on him. If he had, he probably would have been more aware of why he felt a small twinge of resentment. Instead, as if to chase off this lingering and uncomfortable feeling, he instead pushed on to the Heathrow Terminal train. The destination: Kings Cross station in Central London!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              Later, Ailis found himself outside of Paddington station in central London. According to his directions, he had only to walk northeast to the 501 and follow it until he reached Kings cross station. Ailis felt confidence swell within him. After all, he was quite the expert navigator if he did say so himself. With this pride in his heart, and the gentle squeak of his luggage, he pressed on boldly and bravely.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;              Within 5 minutes Ailis made a critical realization of his situation: he had no idea which way was north. Or even, most critically, where on gods green earth he even was at.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          Indeed, with the sky overcast he had no reference for where the sun was and had set off in the wrong direction. As he continued along, he felt himself growing ever more lost with each step. His cheeks inflated into a slight pout as he came to realize his precarious situation. It could be worse, he reasoned internally. After all, he was in a city. One couldn’t well stay lost in a big city, right?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;         But after 10 minutes of walking, he spied a rather spacious green area, then decided to make it his temporary destination to figure out where he was and how to get to where he needed to be. As he passed from the grey and rather oppressive streets through the gate, he noticed the sign.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;           “Victoria gate, Hyde Park”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;              Ailis’ head tilted as they read the sign ‘That sounds rather familiar to me… I don’t know where I heard it… well whatever’ In this short moment of reflection, Ailis settled on simply taking a short break, then figuring out how to get to Kings cross station. After all, he didn’t walk too far, right?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          While he sat on a bench trying to figure out where he was, his eyes drifted around. It was a nice day by English standards. It was rather cool (by Ailis’ standards) at only 20 degrees Celsius; Ailis considered it to be a downright pleasant day. Especially as there was no wind blowing. Families were out and about, enjoying the park and the comfortable day.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          Ailis stopped his gaze on a girl standing by her lonesome. Looking seemingly bored, but gave it little thought. However, after a moment, he realized the girl was making eye contact with him. Which made him feel rather self-conscious and glanced away politely. His gaze then settled back onto the crude map he had as he tried to figure out where he was precisely and where he needed to go.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          What Ailis didn’t know at that moment, is that he made eye contact with something that nobody else in that park could see. Further, he didn’t know it either, but that momentary eye contact aroused curiosity in the girl. Who proceeded to walk over to where he was sitting, then stood off to his side watching him study the map he was reading.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          “Excuse me,” her voice called out, “but are you lost or something?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          Ailis looked up from the map he was studying, then to the girl standing to his left. She was a young girl, about 5 years younger than him or looking about 13 years old. He faces was covered in light freckles, and her brown eyes were framed by a rather modest haircut which suggested firm middle class upbringing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          His cheeks flushed as he responded in a neutral voice which carried little in the way of masculinity, “I’m actually kind of lost. I’m trying to find my way to Kings Cross station. But I seem to be going in the wrong direction I think…” his voice trailed off rather sheepishly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          To the girl, this confirmed that Ailis could see her. Which caused her to grin slightly in response. This subtle change in expression was, however, misinterpreted by Ailis to mean the was amused by his predicament.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          For a moment she stood silently, as if contemplating how to approach the subject. However, she decided to simply offer assistance. After all, it had been so long since she had a conversation with a person such as this. Especially one who is a foreigner by the sound of their accent.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;        “Where are you from?” she asked simply, giving Ailis an expectant look.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;         “Oh, I’m from the United States. It’s a country on the other side of the ocean. I’m here for college” Ailis responded absently.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          “Well, that explains it, everyone knows this is Hyde Park and Kings Cross station is the other way from here” she said while pointing out north.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          Ailis let out a sigh of relief then stood up rather suddenly, looking much brighter than he had mere moments ago. He took a note of North, figured out east and west from there, then turned to look at the girl who helped him out.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;        “Thank you very much for your assistance,” he all but gushed, “Had you not pointed the way, I might have become even more lost and missed my train.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;        “Train?” she said, “Where are you going?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;        “Edinburgh Scotland” Ailis answered happily “I am starting college there”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;        “Hoo… well I hope things go well for you. And please stay safe” the girl intoned.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;         She then stuck out her hand in a friendly manner. Realizing that she wanted to shake hands, Ailis happily returned the gesture. However, as their hands touched, Ailis was momentarily taken aback by the fact that her hand was quite cool and damp to the touch. However, he quickly dismissed this as not really and of his business. After all, people all had their own circumstances.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;         “Thanks. You too. And please, have a fantastic day” Ailis responded, having lapsed into a more friendly tone before turning back to the gate and setting off once again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          Had Ailis looked back, he would have seen the girl walk back towards the small pond, then, as someone crossed between, he and her, she would have vanished seemingly into thin air. However, in time with her disappearance, the waters of the pond were disturbed with ripples, as if something had leapt into them. Ailis had yet to realize it, but he had just had his first encounter with an Asrai. A type of Fae who lived in waters.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          Ailis was also lucky in his encounter. The Asrai are considered a benevolent variety of Fae. Who are characterized as helpful water sprites who only ever hurt others when their own life is threatened. Had it been a malevolent sort of Fae, there was a chance that Ailis might have had a very perilous encounter. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          After the young girl pointed him in the right direction, Ailis eventually was able to locate Kings Cross station. After having raced across London to get there, he leaned over, panting slightly to catch his breath. He didn’t have to rush, as his train was still some time away from departing. But the excitement to get to the Station had made him rather excited to get on with things.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;           Faced with his destination, he allowed himself a moment of reprieve to consider his situation. Here he was, in his home country he barely knew, in a city he only dimly remembered, heading to a place he only ever visited once. He realized he was actually kind of excited. Excited to see where his mother grew up, played, made friends, and fell in love. He was excited at the prospect of meeting new people, studying, and eventually getting a good job.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          Yet, underneath this excitement was a sense of unease. Worry at the same time that he would hate it, that he didn’t belong, that something bad would happen. That he would be stuck with nothing. Lost and alone in a strange place with nothing to support him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          More than that, he felt a deeper unease in his heart. He had no way of framing it with words. But there was a strong sense that something even bigger was wrong. Something he couldn’t frame with words. As if the very concept of the words Ailis used to describe himself were somehow wrong. As if he was deceiving himself and trying to play a part he was not suited for.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;          After a moment of trepidation, he brushed off these thoughts. Then, he entered the station. Once again, he found himself swept away with the tide of people, though it was more orderly than the Airport. Which allowed him to find his way to the train he was to board and eventually to his assigned berth. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              There was a sort of solace in knowing that he had a small room to himself. He wouldn’t have to deal with other people, nor would he have to face odd questions which, to him, seemed to make any sense. It was one thing to ask about who he was, it was quite another to assume he was a woman just because he didn’t look very manly! His thoughts stewed like this as he looked down at his feet. Sure, he reasoned, maybe he didn’t look the largest, and sure, he had a small frame and never quite developed very masculine features…&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;            Clearly, it turned out, the previous encounters at the Airport and the awareness that he wasn’t quite a man like he figured, were, in fact, weighing on his mind. Enough so that he barely even noticed when the train began to move.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;              As he contemplated this, his gaze drifted to the outside, his reflection clearly visible. To him. His features were normal. Auburn hair that was a little long but well kept, turquoise blue eyes, hair sitting just off his shoulders, and his face was just… neutral? Right? He had no way of knowing that his features were actually softer than a typical mans. Less angular, more rounded. His body, which he always assumed he was skinny, was actually more adequately compared to a woman’s, with very gentle muscle tones, and features which were softer than a man’s.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;              Ailis lacked the ability to really understand how different he was to what a typical man actually looked like. This is because he had closed off his awareness by assuming his own features were a baseline. Rather than the variance that it truly was. Had he, he might have sought consultation at a hospital and would have come to understand more about who and what he was years before this moment when he stewed over the various indignities he encountered. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              He also was entirely unaware that there was actually a good cause for this. And it rested with his mother who had died in a car crash some years before… He did, after all, looking surprisingly similar to her. Having seemingly only inherited his father’s good eyesight. However, since they had died rather suddenly, and he was not properly cared for at the orphanage, he remained blissfully ignorant of just how different he truly was.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;              With the train’s movement, he allowed himself to relax a little. His hand idly tapped the seats handrest in a rhythmic pattern. As if one hand were playing the piano. Which, in a way, it was. It happened to be one of his more beloved hobbies. Playing American songs on the Piano.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;              When he was younger, he dealt with the aftermath of his parents’ death by indulging in the last thing his mother had taught him, which was how to play music. He came to love it and regarded memories of sitting by her while learning different chords, how to move his hands and fingers separately of each other, and memorizing songs that she had taught him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:left"&gt;              In a way, he had come to see music as a way of holding dearly onto something precious that he had lost so many years before. It had, in a way, come to eclipse his other love of astronomy. Though he was as yet unaware of such a thing having happened. Instead, he blithely believed one was more important than the other, and that he only had the option to master one and that the other would be neglected. He was rather foolish for such narrow views…&lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;              Lost in these murky thoughts, he watched idly as the train slowly departed the London metro area, the high rises and built-up city giving way to first suburban neighborhoods and town squares, to eventually rural countryside. The train plowing along at a high-speed pace. Taking him closer and closer to his mothers birth place and his college destination. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;End of First Chapter&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Post script:&lt;/em&gt; This entire story was almost something else entirely. However, as I began working on it, I was nudged in a slightly different direction with the story by a few friends suggestions. Which helped to really bring the story into focus. A lot of my references for the original story will, however, wind up getting used again. This is going to be a bit of a slow burn novel and as of writing this, I only really have about 6 chapters dialed in as to what I want them to contain, and a larger overview of where the story is going. If you've taken the time to read this, I appreciate you taking the time. If you wish to leave suggestions, I am open to them. However, there are some formatting issues which appeared when I transferred this over to scribblehubs interface. It is annoying. But now that I know of them. I can take preventative measures to ensure it doesn't happen in the future. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
