      <title>Insecurity</title>
      <author> suecee </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1774359/insecurity/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1774359-insecurity/chapter/1774369/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">aab0434adb052ec95577fc5538f088bf63f266a2</guid>
      <pubDate>Tue, 02 Sep 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Dreams that are repressed, find a way to become real.&lt;br /&gt; Carl had dreamed a dream for years. Then, facing bad news at work, he just had to take that last chance to live it, even if it meant deceiving his boss.&lt;br /&gt; Or was he deceiving himself?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1774359-insecurity/chapter/1774369/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;1– Staring at the cliff’s edge&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Carl sat hunched over his computer, his eyes glued to the screen, looking tables of data analysis but not seeing them. His heartbeat quickened as the clock ticked closer to five. For most others it had been an ordinary Friday in the office.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But he'd received an email from Amanda, his manager, asking him to stay back for a chat.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It had distracted him all day. Normally, unlike many co-workers, he would treat even Friday afternoons as important productive time: he was driven by the need to be useful, to be seen as reliable, good in a crisis. But this whole week he'd been erratic, and he knew it. He had been working unproductively for days, and every day, many glances at the clock reminded him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He tried not to be obsessive about his performance, though he knew that was just how he was. How else could he have delivered so well for the company these last two years? Masses of bug-free code; the flawless documentation and other work that the company and - he'd thought, Amanda - appreciated. He had a tendency to latch onto an idea, give it everything, aim for perfection in all details, unless and until proven that it was unreachable.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Being a perfectionist at work wasn't so much a problem. It was his private obsession: he was always striving for some kind of ideal. But he hated himself for how it overcame him. For weeks he'd tried to suppress it, and by working longer hours and at the same level of attention, to distract himself. Even though he had tried before to purge himself of the obsession.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;At 28, he had a long career ahead of him, but in his personal life, the eternity seemed behind him: the years without a girlfriend, despite meeting a number of women he felt safe with. He was amazed that any of them could like this average-height, narrow-shouldered, shy man who didn't like eye contact.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Then some would become more friendly, and his mind would reach ahead to the day when he would have to confess his secret. Shame would fill him, and he would run away, break contact.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He tried to understand it. He read widely of psychological works, to explain his condition, so as to gain control. But in the end, he couldn't pin himself down. The thought of seeking professional help scared him too much. He thought he knew all the possible outcomes. Some of the possible outcomes would mean a total change of life. But at the least, it meant moving on, which he didn't like.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The truth, though he couldn't admit it to himself, was that he liked his secret behaviour.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The self-reflection and the constant obsession were now making for poor work. The weeks of poor performance had made it worse, made him depressed, so that he took more solace in his private concerns. But it had gone on far too long and he knew it. His boss seemed to be ignoring him lately, and he'd heard rumours of downsizing. He was convinced his time was nearly up here.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Having accepted that fate in advance, he felt fear. But also, he realised, some freedom, with little to lose. He would decide how he would exit the company. Get something he wanted - no, desired, dreamed of - but it wasn't money. Nor a good reference. He knew what he wanted to ask for. He was pretty sure he had the courage to make the request to his manager. And Amanda seemed to hold respect for him, at least as a person, if not as a worker.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Now Amanda had asked him in for a meeting, without mentioning a reason. That was always a bad sign.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;So why not ask for a special favour, "like a condemned man's final meal" he mused. Man, indeed. He hoped she would grant him on his way out. Now was a good time: Amanda had last week, by chance, mentioned the subject herself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The office buzz faded into a distant murmur, the last few employees dragging their feet out the door. The quiet hum of the air-conditioning was the only sound that filled the now-desolate room. Right on five pm, Amanda marched in, clearly in a hurry. Carl took a deep breath, stood up, and would have straightened his tie if he didn't loathe such things. His nerves were jangling.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He approached Amanda's office, the polished wood door seeming like the last protection from the conversation. Knocking gently, he heard her voice, clear and unassuming, beckon him inside. She looked up from her paperwork, her eyes kind, her expression one of genuine concern. Not angry any more?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Carl had always found her unassuming features and simple appearance reassuring. He felt he could trust Amanda.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"You've been looking a bit stressed, Carl," she began, setting her pen aside. "Is everything okay?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her question hung in the air like a gentle prodding, coaxing him to unravel his tangled thoughts. He took a tentative step into the room, the plush carpet muffling his footsteps. Nodding, he took a seat in the chair opposite her desk, his eyes darting around the neatly organized space, searching for an escape from his own tumultuous mind. "It's just...that story you told last week, about that person you used to work  with," he finally murmured, his voice barely above a whisper.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Amanda leaned back in her chair, her gaze never leaving him. "Yes?" she prompted. She had spoken to her whole team about the new diversity policies, and she was pleased that it had gotten through. Funny that Carl was talking about it. "Jay? The one who went through a transition?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Carl swallowed hard, feeling the weight of his secret pressing down on him. "Yeah. Sounded like you understood them." He steered carefully into the topic, preparing his story. He tried not to think of it as a lie.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I do have some experience of gender issues," she said. She wondered if she should tell him how much, but waited for him to go on.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Because I wanted to tell you..it...it really made me think," he admitted. "It's like you were talking about something I've...thought about for a long time." That much was true.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Amanda leaned forward, her elbows resting on her desk, her eyes softening. "What do you mean, Carl?" Her gaze was kind: she had always seen Carl as a pleasant-looking and calm, somewhat gentle, even if a bit over-focussed - but that was not rare for IT.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Well," Carl began, his voice trembling slightly, "I... I've always felt like I'm not truly...me. Like there's this other person inside, waiting to come out." He knew he was being a bit vague. He wanted to hide his strongest, most guilty feelings.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Amanda's leaned forward. "I'd like to hear more, if you're okay with that?" she asked, her tone gentle yet firm.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Carl took a deep breath and clasped his hands tightly. "It's just that, ever since I was a kid, I've...I've been kind of trans, myself," he confessed, the words spilling out like a dam breaking. "It's something I've kept hidden, but hearing that story made me feel...less alone, I guess."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Amanda's expression shifted from concern to one of understanding. "You're talking about you being transgender?" she asked, her voice calm and measured.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Carl nodded, his cheeks flushing a deep red. "Yeah," he murmured, his eyes dropping to his lap. "Gender dysphoria. I'm not the gender I want to appear as. But it's not something I can talk about with just anyone. "I hoped that you....." he trailed off.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Amanda leaned back in her chair, her gaze never leaving him. She was surprised by Carl's admission, but she knew that opening up about such a deeply personal subject took courage, especially in the corporate jungle. "Carl," she said, her voice measured and calm, "I can see this really matters to you, so it matters to me. As your manager. I want everyone on my team to be comfortable and, well, productive."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He dared to meet her gaze. Her words sounded a bit formal, but the sincerity and warmth in her voice, said that she could be bothered. Maybe she really was a friend? Maybe she would give him a good reference after all?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She looked at him, saw how jangled he was, a mixture of embarrassment and ... pent-up energy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"This is deeply personal, Carl, and I'm ... well, I'm glad you were able to trust me with this. You know I'll keep it private - not even Employee Assistance need to know - unless you want to talk to them?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He shook his head. "No, I'm beyond that."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"It sounds like you've thought a lot about this. I don't have the professional qualifications to work with you on it, but I am happy to talk about it, help you find what you need."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;She waited. Carl looked around the room, clasping and unclasping his hands.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;She got up, put her phone on hold, and rolled her chair around to his side of her desk. Put a hand on his shoulder.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Help me here, Carl. I want to understand. Where are you at?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;He looked down. "I've been, you know, doing it at home for a long time. Since I was ten. Dressing up."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;She paused before adding softly, "Dressing as a woman?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;He felt excited just to hear someone say it, but ashamed as well. He put his face in his hands. Did he really want this? God knew he'd dreamed about this conversation, for years. Did he really want to go through with this? But he'd admitted his urge. Amanda's image of him was in the pits now anyway.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Mm-hm."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;He dared to look her in the eye again. She looked so calm.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"That's one huge step you've taken today, Carl, I mean, telling me. What do you want me to do for you?" she asked, her voice steady.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;His thoughts were jumbled now, like water over a waterfall, but all going the same way. "Would you really help me? You, you're being so calm about it."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Of course," Amanda said. She stayed calm, yet was struggling inside, with the shock: she'd not seen any clue of this. Suddenly she had an image of him in women's clothes. It struck her that his slim build and finer features would help - then abruptly she brought her focus back.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;The truth was, she valued him. Carl behaved like most male workers, even if slightly non-social and awkward. But she was rarely impressed by personality: results mattered to her, and integrity. Carl was, if anything, over-committed to work, something she saw in herself. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Carl, I have always liked your attitude, and your values. You and I have something in common there. And, I know that people with gender discomfort are genuine, as you always are."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;He felt a tiny pang of guilt. Was he truly being honest about his reasons? Even with himself? But he felt a great desire to leap into the warm and trusting space Amanda had created. She was only the second person he'd ever told about his dressing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;He felt his eyes tearing up. His desires also welled up.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"What would you like help with first, Carl?" She was thinking about whom in HR would deal with this.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;He blurted out, "Coming to work." There, he'd said it. What he'd imagined for months. Imagined in fine detail, even prepared for, just to experience some of it....&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;She waited, guessing what was coming.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"I'd like to try out...coming to work as a woman. It's...a big thing for me, Amanda."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;It was written on his face, on the laboured breathing. "It is a big step. And work is a big part of our lives." She paused. "You don't live with anyone, I gather."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;He shook his head.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"That's quite brave, Carl, to take this on alone," she said, her voice measured. "But I understand your need to explore." Once again she paused to give him space.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Yeah, I know it could create problems, I don't want to make trouble, and you've got enough rules and policies and stuff to manage without this-"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Don't worry about that, Carl. Actually, I do know that the company has recently setup gender diversity policies, which is a big deal these days, I know."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Yes, I've read them." He had, in preparation for arguing his case.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Good. And as you may know, we like to show that we're progressive, here." Amanda admitted to herself that she had her own reasons as well. "The new policy states that any employee with gender dysphoria may present in the workplace as their preferred gender, and expect to be supported in doing so by management, with appropriate arrangements to ensure co-worker acceptance.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"So...your timing is pretty good. In fact, you'd be an example - actually the first person to be helped by the new attitudes. And personally? I'd be proud to use them for you."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;She was smiling at him. This was such a turnaround - he'd expected an argument, criticism, or Amanda cutting him short by talking about being let go. Now...not only was she telling him how valued he was, he might become more important to her. He felt so grateful. The "shock them on the way out" motive had vanished, leaving questions.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;Was it still important enough?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;How deep was his need to present as female? What if it passed after he'd done this and had to embarrass himself by coming back? Assuming he still had a job...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;He decided to tread more gently. Maybe give himself an escape route?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"I'm...That's so nice of you, Amanda. I don't want to shock anyone, or make it difficult. Maybe I can start small?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Not a problem, Carl, that's a great idea, it's what usually happens..."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;Usually? He wondered.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;She continued. "And I can see you're struggling a little. That's normal - I think. Perhaps we leave it for now? You've lots to think about."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;He almost leaped to his feet, in relief. An escape!. "Yes, yes, Amanda, I've got to think this through." He pushed the chair in.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Carl, wait, wait...don't rush off. Please sit down."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;Oh no, here it comes, he thought.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Carl, I'm trying to help here. Now, you were so relieved when I said I wanted help you in your - your gender journey. I'm quite serious about that. It means something to me, personally.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;'Come here as a woman'. The words electrified him again. How could he walk out now? I have to jump in, he thought. If I think about it...I'll never do it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;Amanda said, "Shall we meet with an HR person about this? We can start planning things out, take our time."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"How - how about I try it out for a day. Do it anonymously. Pretend to be a visitor? Then I can leave if I need to." And, he thought, only Amanda need know.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;Amanda was surprised. She paused for a moment, considering his words. He seemed very scared, but also driven.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;She usually preferred cutting to the chase. Carl seemed energised like he'd never been, which touched her. And this might be a good chance to be a leader in these things.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;"Okay," she finally said. "Let's talk about that. How about this: we start with you coming in on a weekend afternoon, when the office is usually empty, but with me here. We'll go from there."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;She talked to him about the details.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;Was he able to dress in clothes suitable for the office? She was impressed to hear that he'd noted what women wore in the building, and steered him toward safer options - much like what she wore, such as loose slacks, or a knee-length skirt in black or navy, topped with a blazer or cardigan.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;She would get a generic visitor's pass for him, no name on it. She would be in the office beforehand, to meet him. He would stay only for as long as he wanted.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;Would he need a lift to or from work? He said he would prefer to walk, as he lived nearby and it would calm him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;She could see him relax visibly. She knew his quick mind was sorting through the details - or already had.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt;As they parted with a plan for next Saturday, a week from today, she took a breath. She hoped it would go smoothly. She would have to prepare herself, to greet Carl normally - yet differently. She knew she would have to avoid looking critical. He would want to be treated like a business woman.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="min-height:1em"&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
